<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 2; Column 3; Opinion Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1190 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE MEDIA HAVE GOT IT WRONG -- MILITARY SAFETY PERFORMANCE IN GULF IS 
EXEMPLARY; 
</P>
<P>
IRAQ: ALTHOUGH 31 AMERICANS HAVE DIED, THE CASUALTY RATE IS FAR BELOW WHAT CAN 
BE EXPECTED WHEN 200,000 SOLDIERS ASSEMBLE IN A HARSH ENVIRONMENT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jim Blackwell, Jim Blackwell is deputy director of political-military 
studies at the Center for Strategic and International Studies. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So far, 31 American soldiers have been killed in accidents during Operation 
Desert Shield in the Persian Gulf. Is this too many? How should the accidental 
injury and fatality rates be interpreted? The media, faced with a lull in 
military action, has mistakenly transformed the gulf rates into an issue. 
</P>
<P>
In August, a number of Army soldiers were seriously injured when their 
Jeep-like High-Mobility Multi-Purpose Wheeled Vehicle overturned in the desert 
sands. In September, a Marine Corps CH-53 Super Stallion helicopter suffered a 
mechanical failure while idling on the runway, causing it to overturn and burn. 
A number of accidents have involved low-level flying, some at night. All 
services have had their share of misfortune: Air Force, 6 incidents; Army, 2; 
Marine Corps, 2, and Navy, 1. 
</P>
<P>
Still, is the accident rate in the gulf excessive, as the media seem to be 
suggesting? And what about the design, engineering and production of the 
equipment in use in the gulf? Is it seriously flawed and thus the cause of the 
accidents, as some in the media have argued? 
</P>
<P>
In light of past experience, the U.S. military's performance is well within the 
bounds of expectation, considering the tempo of required combat training in a 
particularly harsh environment. And there is no evidence to tie the equipment 
deployed in the gulf to the reported accidents. Although equipment failure is 
frequently the cause of accidents, other factors include poor maintenance, 
operator error, physical fatigue and failure to follow proper procedures. In 
most investigations of accidents, it is not easy to isolate the cause. 
</P>
<P>
Using military historian Trevor Dupuy's calculations of the average rate of 
non-combat casualties, the 200,000-strong Middle East force should have 
sustained about 400 casualties by now. This rate has been relatively constant 
for all military forces of all nations since the 19th Century. The American 
experience regarding non-combat accidents during World War II, Korea and 
Vietnam, according to Dupuy, was not much different. 
</P>
<P>
While any death or injury is regrettable, the U.S. Central Command's record in 
the gulf so far is thus exemplary. Compare a similarly large military exercise 
in Europe in 1986 that involved 200,000 American soldiers for about a month. In 
the operation, accident, fatality and injury rates were closer to Dupuy's 
estimates than to those in Desert Shield. 
</P>
<P>
But historical comparisons are useful only up to a point, and important 
questions have been raised about the Persian Gulf accidents. Some armchair 
strategists, for example, have challenged the prudence of flying aircraft low 
and fast at night. This argument, however, begs the question of how to train 
helicopter and fighter crews to contend with the conditions under which they 
will actually fly combat missions. 
</P>
<P>
The alternative of flying exclusively in broad daylight, at altitudes and 
speeds easily targetable by enemy anti-aircraft weapons and even small-arms 
fire, is obviously unacceptable. The responsibility of the gulf military 
commanders is to exploit every advantage they can from their superior 
technology -- and, right now, U.S. forces own the night. Many lives will be 
saved by maintaining the required level of preparedness to strike Iraqi forces 
in darkness. It should be recalled that all hits by enemy fire on U.S. 
helicopters in Panama occurred during daylight. 
</P>
<P>
In an important sense, every accident is avoidable. Military commanders bear 
the sole burden of responsibility and accountability not only for accomplishing 
their mission, but also for the safety, health and welfare of the U.S. citizens 
entrusted to their command. For every mishap that occurs in their units, 
military leaders must identify, if possible, the act or omission that caused 
the accident and take firm action to ensure that those conditions do not recur. 
</P>
<P>
There is an unwritten understanding among that very small circle of officers 
selected for command that "good leaders have low accident rates." This means 
that if you want to keep your command when you have a spate of accidents, you 
had better do something to get your rate down. This is apparently what happened 
in 1989 when the U.S. Navy's response to a spate of accidents at sea was to 
shut down all fleet operations for 48 hours in order to review safety 
procedures. The recent 12-hour suspension of operations by U.S. air forces in 
the Persian Gulf was similarly motivated. 
</P>
<P>
All leaders have to confront the consequences of safety conditions in their 
units. The most difficult piece of correspondence I have had to write is the 
letter of notification to next of kin that a member of my command had lost his 
life because of a training accident. There is no adequate consolation for 
bereaved parents and loved ones that their son died "in the line of duty." It 
is a responsibility that weighs heavily on all good commanders; whenever a 
military leader is found lacking in such care and concern, he or she is 
unworthy of the authority entrusted to them and should be relieved. 
</P>
<P>
But military leaders also know that war is risky beyond anticipation. Only the 
commander has the responsibility to ensure that those who must fight in the 
field, on the bridge or in the cockpit are fully prepared to cope with the 
rigors of combat. And only he or she best knows the state of a unit's 
readiness, acclimation to the environment and how it stacks up against the 
mission to be performed. As a result, commanding officers endure the tension 
imposed by the requirement to direct the physical and mental preparations for 
combat in the most realistic manner possible, while at the same time not 
risking unduly the lives of their people while training. 
</P>
<P>
Such tension is healthy since both objectives -- realism in training and 
proficiency in combat -- are necessary. The trade-off in risks is well 
understood by those who have commanded in combat and afterward evaluated their 
preparation for real battle. 
</P>
<P>
When combat is imminent, as it appears it may be in the Persian Gulf, the 
commanders preparing the forces will correctly enhance their chances for 
success in battle by accepting some measure of risk in preparatory training. 
This means that soldiers must fire live ammunition in close proximity to their 
colleagues, that commanders and staffs must coordinate long-range artillery 
fire, close air support and naval gunfire. It also means that everyone in the 
gulf -- especially supporting personnel at locations likely to be targeted by 
Iraq -- must regularly be exposed to nonlethal doses of chemical weapons while 
working in their protective gear. During such exercises, some people are going 
to be hurt, but unless the accident rate rises beyond the level anticipated in 
combat, even if the rise is dramatic, we should not look for or create an issue 
where there is none. 
</P>
<P>
Military commanders in the gulf already have their hands full leading their 
organizations, conducting realistic and strenuous training, promoting high 
morale and, sadly, writing those few -- so far -- next-of-kin notification 
letters. They will not need to be further burdened by responding to uninformed 
criticism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, CATHERINE KANNER / for The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
